02307cam a2200337 i 20161228113111.0m     o  d        cr unu||||||||121212s2013    miua    ob   s001 0 eng d  a2012042609  a9780472118748q(hardback : acid-free paper)  a9780472029082q(e-book)7 a10.3998/mpub.5070882  aMiUbengcMiU00aPN2193.E86bH375 201300a792.02/232231 aHarding, James Martin,d1958-14aThe ghosts of the avant-garde(s) :bexorcising experimental theater and performance /cJames M. Harding. 1aAnn Arbor :bThe University of Michigan Press,c[2013]  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aIncludes bibliographical references and index.  a" Pronouncements such as "the avant-garde is dead," argues James M. Harding, have suggested a unified history or theory of the avant-garde. His book examines the diversity and plurality of avant-garde gestures and expressions to suggest "avant-garde pluralities" and how an appreciation of these pluralities enables a more dynamic and increasingly global understanding of vanguardism in the performing arts. In pursuing this goal, the book not only surveys a wide variety of canonical and noncanonical examples of avant-garde performance, but also develops a range of theoretical paradigms that defend the haunting cultural and political significance of avant-garde expressions beyond what critics have presumed to be the death of the avant-garde. The Ghosts of the Avant-Garde(s) offers a strikingly new perspective not only on key controversies and debates within avant-garde studies but also on contemporary forms of avant-garde expression within a global political economy"--cProvided by publisher.  aDescription based on information from the publisher. 0aExperimental theaterxHistory and criticism. 0aExperimental dramaxHistory and criticism. 4aElectronic books.2 aMichigan Publishing (University of Michigan)epublisher.40zAccess to the Michigan Publishing online version:uhttps://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.5070882